    <node id="1. The two &quot;dangerous, invisible viruses&quot; that the speaker identifies are COVID-19 and race-based hatred, hate speech, and anti-black racism. The speaker emphasizes that while Canadians are dealing with the visible threat of the coronavirus pandemic, they must also acknowledge and address the less visible but equally dangerous virus of systemic racism and discrimination against Black individuals in Canada.&#10;2. It is important for Canadians to acknowledge that black lives matter because anti-black racism and violence against Black people are ongoing issues in Canada, not just in the United States. The speaker highlights specific cases of police violence and calls for justice for Regis Korchinski-Paquet, a Black woman killed in Toronto, as well as a Black trans woman who died in suspicious circumstances during an interaction with the police. The speaker emphasizes that people are angry and frustrated about the ongoing violence and discrimination faced by Black individuals, and the need for concrete actions and commitments to end these unjust practices." />
    <node id=")&#10;Content: Thank you, Mr. Chair. This is indeed a difficult day. It's a difficult week. These have been difficult weeks. I stand here and want to begin by acknowledging that we are all on the traditional territory of the Algonquin peoples, and again to say meegwetch, on a day like this when we're focusing on something so painful that really is beyond partisanship and that should bind us together as people who say we cannot tolerate racism, not in this country. But we know it's here. As the Prime Minister just said, Racism never has a place in this country. But we know it's here and we know it's living with us. We are facing, in this pandemic, two dangerous, invisible viruses. One is COVID-19 and the other one we've tolerated far too long, which is race-based hatred, hate speech and anti-black racism. Yes, black lives matter. I want to do nothing but just chant it in this place until we all stand together and say, Black lives matter. What we are seeing in the murder of George Floyd is exactly as my colleague from the Bloc Qubcois said: George Floyd is not a victim of racism; he is another victim" />
