    <node id="1. Ban on Certain Firearms: The Canadian government has recently banned certain firearms, including some that were not designed for hunting or sport shooting but for military use. This ban has been criticized by some, including the member for Medicine Hat-Cardston-Warner, for prioritizing political interests over the safety and protection of Canadians.&#10;2. Lack of Notice on Banned Firearms List Changes: Mr. Glen Motz questioned why there was no notice given to firearm owners, retailers, or the police regarding changes to the banned firearms list. Hon. Bill Blair stated that the RCMP continues to do diligence to keep Canadians safe by updating the list, but no formal notices have been provided.&#10;3. No Records of Non-Restricted Firearm Transfers: Mr. Glen Motz asked how many firearms have been transferred between licensed gun owners and/or retailers since May 1. Hon. Bill Blair admitted that the government does not keep records of such transfers for non-restricted firearms.&#10;4. Absence of Cost Estimate for Buyback Program: The government has proposed a firearms buyback program, but no cost estimate has been provided in the transcript.&#10;&#10;These measures have led to criticism that the Canadian government is prioritizing political interests over the safety and protection of Canadians, as well as creating difficulties for legal gun owners and businesses while not effectively addressing the root causes of gun violence." />
    <node id="The Prime Minister's role in providing wage subsidies to organizations and companies during the pandemic, as explained by the Acting Chair (Mr. Bruce Stanton) and the Right Hon. Justin Trudeau, is to ensure that people will receive their paycheques in order to support their families and pay their rent. This is in response to concerns from people across the country, including Quebec, who are worried about their jobs due to the crisis caused by the pandemic. The goal of this measure is to protect Canadians across the country who are working for businesses facing a reduction in revenue, so that they have enough money to meet the challenges they are facing during the pandemic and support the economy." />
