    <edge source="The transcript shows a debate between various political figures in Canada regarding systemic anti-black and anti-indigenous racism, including the issue of racial profiling in policing. The Minister of Public Safety, Bill Blair, acknowledges that racial profiling is unlawful and contrary to the Charter of Rights and Freedoms and the Canadian Human Rights Act. He also mentions that they are working diligently within federal agencies to ensure that all officers receive training on culturally competent and bias-free delivery of service. However, he did not explicitly commit to ending street checks or carding immediately.&#10;&#10;In summary, while there is recognition of the issue of systemic anti-black and anti-indigenous racism in Canada, including racial profiling in policing, and a commitment to training on culturally competent and bias-free delivery of service, there is no explicit commitment to ending the practice of street checks or carding immediately." target="1. The two &quot;dangerous, invisible viruses&quot; that the speaker identifies are COVID-19 and race-based hatred, hate speech, and anti-black racism. The speaker emphasizes that while Canadians are dealing with the visible threat of the coronavirus pandemic, they must also acknowledge and address the less visible but equally dangerous virus of systemic racism and discrimination against Black individuals in Canada.&#10;2. It is important for Canadians to acknowledge that black lives matter because anti-black racism and violence against Black people are ongoing issues in Canada, not just in the United States. The speaker highlights specific cases of police violence and calls for justice for Regis Korchinski-Paquet, a Black woman killed in Toronto, as well as a Black trans woman who died in suspicious circumstances during an interaction with the police. The speaker emphasizes that people are angry and frustrated about the ongoing violence and discrimination faced by Black individuals, and the need for concrete actions and commitments to end these unjust practices.">
      <data key="d0">1</data>
    </edge>
    <edge source=" police, the architect of this country's largest profiling program under the guise of street checks or carding, was made this country's Minister of Public Safety by this Prime Minister. As the tragic consequence of the unlawful, unconstitutional and racist practices in Toronto, black people are 20 times more likely than non-black people to be murdered by police. Does the Minister of Public Safety now admit that the police practice of street checks and carding is in fact a significant factor in Canada's systemic anti-black and anti-indigenous racism, and will he act to immediately end it today?&#10;Speaker: Hon. Bill Blair&#10;Content: Mr. Chair, let me be very clear. First of all, every Canadian is entitled to bias-free and culturally competent policing. I know from experience that there is nothing more corrosive to the relationship of trust that must exist between the police and racialized communities than the issue of racism or the biased influences of those decisions. Mr. Chair, racial profiling is not only abhorrent and unacceptable, it's in fact unlawful. It's contrary to the Charter of Rights and Freedoms and it's contrary to the Canadian Human Rights Act. We are working diligently within all of the federal agencies under my purview to ensure that all officers receive training" target="1. Hon. Patty Hajdu commits to working with the ALS community and manufacturers of drugs for ALS to expedite drug approval in a safe and affordable way for all Canadians.&#10;2. Hon. Bardish Chagger, on behalf of the government, commits to listening more, acknowledging that racism is alive in Canada, and working across departments to ensure better collection of disaggregated data. While not explicitly stated, she implies this will be a legal requirement as the immunity task force is already providing disaggregated data to decision-makers.&#10;3. Hon. Bill Blair, as Minister of Public Safety, commits to ensuring all federal agencies under his purview provide training on culturally competent and bias-free delivery of service and creating a diverse workforce that reflects and respects the diverse people of this country.&#10;&#10;Note: The commitments mentioned above are in response to Mr. Matthew Green's requests, but they were made by various cabinet ministers other than Hon. Patty Hajdu. It is not explicitly stated whether she is willing to make any further commitments regarding anti-black racism beyond her commitment related to ALS.">
